      "title": "Split the mixed-scope agent-browser mega-suite into focused test files",
      "description": "Principles: Localize change, Operational hygiene.\n\nEvidence:\n- path: test/agent-browser.test.ts:1-249 :: one file owns shared harness setup for runtime, temp, process, results, and extension integration tests.\n- path: test/agent-browser.test.ts:254-3436 :: the same file contains roughly the full repo test surface, from pure helper tests through process and extension lifecycle integration.\n- workflow: wc -l test/agent-browser.test.ts test/verify-package.test.ts :: agent-browser.test.ts is 3483 lines while the only other test file is 152 lines.\n- workflow: rg -c \"const tempDir = await mkdtemp\\(\" test/agent-browser.test.ts :: 34 repeated temp-dir bootstrap sites.\n- workflow: rg -c \"await withPatchedEnv\\(\" test/agent-browser.test.ts :: 35 repeated env-patching sites.\n- workflow: rg -c \"runExtensionEvent\\(harness.handlers, \\\"session_start\\\"\" test/agent-browser.test.ts :: 17 repeated session-start bootstrap sites.\n\nWhy it matters: failures are harder to localize, fixture reuse is mostly copy-paste, and a small change to one subsystem forces maintainers to navigate a single 3.4k-line test file that mixes unit and higher-level integration concerns.\n\nMinimal proposed fix: split the suite by subject area such as runtime, temp/process, results, and extension integration, and extract common harness/bootstrap helpers into shared test utilities.\n\nAcceptance criteria: the large mixed-scope file is removed or substantially reduced in favor of focused test files and shared fixtures; `npm run verify` still passes; maintainers can run subject-specific test files without scanning a monolithic suite.",
